@NODE overenglish "RealTimeWatch/Überblick/english"
@{JCENTER}

@{B}RealTimeWatch V1.6@{UB}@{PAR}
@{JLEFT}

What is RealTimeWatch ?@{PAR}

I am sure, you at least once encountered the situation, that some program
messed up your Amiga's hardware clock. Besides, that it is a nuisance to
adjust the clock again, there is also some software, which does not work
anymore, if your system time is not what it should be.@{PAR}

The most obvious example is the "V43 picture.datatype", which only works
for four months, and then has to be replaced by the new version (very sick
concept, if you ask me). But even good old ToolManager2.1 refuses to work,
if your hardware clock gets messed up.@{PAR}

So, what to do ? First, I was thinking about some MMU protection of the
address range of the hardware clock - but who has an actually working MMU ?
For an Amiga user, this is still an exception. The next way to go was a
kind of watchdog for the hardware clock, that keeps track of the real time
-> RealTimeWatch was born !@{PAR}

The symptoms of messing up the hardware clock are two: first some program
goes mad, writing to random addresses, preferably the hardware clock's.
After that a reboot occurs (by accident or purpose), and the wrong time is
set as the system time. Now it's clear: you have to check the hardware clock
every now and then, to recognize any abnormal changes, then you can reset
the clock to it's normal state.@{PAR}

The only thing to look out for, is, that during summer, the clock can
"legally" be changed by a quantum of 60 minutes by the user. But as the
overwriting of the hardware clock changes the date by an amount of years,
that's not a real problem.@{PAR}

What, if a gone-mad program changes your hardware clock and then provokes
a reboot ? Bad luck - or isn't it ? You could have saved the correct time
before, and write it back after reboot. Of course, RealTimeWatch is capable
to do that (see option @{" LOGFILE " link optloge 0}). It saves the time
at program startup and compares it to the previous saved time, if there is
any.@{PAR}

Now there is a caveat for users, who never reboot or turn off their Amiga,
e.g. mailbox hosts. RealTimeWatch would only be started once, so there is
no chance of comparing an older date. Nevertheless, you still have the
"online" check, after all.@{PAR}

@ENDNODE

@NODE hardenglish "RealTimeWatch/Anforderungen/english"


Requirements of RealTimeWatch to your Amiga:@{PAR}
@{LINDENT 4}

·@{LINDENT 6} at least Kickstart/Workbench 2.04 (Version 37). Version 36 (early
A3000) does NOT work !
@{LINDENT 4}

·@{LINDENT 6} at least an MC68020 processor. Don't slow down the development of
the Amiga by sticking to obsolete processor types as the MC68000 or MC68010. Keep
in mind, that the MC68000 has been developed in 1979, which was 18 years before
today !
@{LINDENT 4}

·@{LINDENT 6} a hardware clock, which is supported by the system functions
(battclock.resource). "Naked" Amiga 500+, 600, 1200 will NOT work ! But many
memory and accelerator boards supply a hardware clock.
@{LINDENT 4}

·@{LINDENT 6} there should be approximately 10 kByte of memory (RAM) available,
to start RealTimeWatch.
@{LINDENT 4}

@ENDNODE

@NODE instenglish "RealTimeWatch/Installation/english"


@{B}A note about installation:@{UB}


You only need the english or german executable, depending, which language
you are more capable of.@{PAR}

There are "RealTimeWatch_deutsch" and "RealTimeWatch_english". Rename
the appropriate one to "RealTimeWatch" and copy it into "C:", try to use
something like this:@{PAR}
@{CODE}
@{JCENTER}@{B}copy RealTimeWatch_english C:RealTimeWatch@{UB}
@{JLEFT}@{PARD}

This assumes, you are working in a shell environment and have cd-ed to
where you extracted RTWatch.@{PAR}

From Workbench, select "Window/Show Contents/Show All Files" from the
menu and double click on either "RealTimeWatch_english" or
"RealTimeWatch_deutsch". A requester should open with the selected file
name in it. Now just type the above line into the string gadget.
Finally select the OK button.That's just the same as if it had been
typed from shell.@{PAR}

The last step is to modify your startup-sequence. Load it into you
favorite text editor and insert the following line after the line saying
"SetPatch QUIET ...":@{PAR}
@{CODE}
@{JCENTER}@{B}Run <>NIL: C:RealTimeWatch@{UB}
@{JLEFT}@{PARD}

Also take a look at the @{" Options " link optenglish 0} !@{PAR}

Save this to disk and next time you reboot, you have a better protection
of your hardware clock.@{PAR}

@{JCENTER}@{CODE}@{B}
! IMPORTANT ! IMPORTANT ! IMPORTANT !

+---------------------------------------+
| I STRONGLY ADVICE YOU TO CHECK THE    |
| PROGRAM FOR VIRUSES BEFORE USING IT ! |
+---------------------------------------+

! IMPORTANT ! IMPORTANT ! IMPORTANT !

@ENDNODE

@NODE optenglish "RealTimeWatch/Optionen/english"


@{B}FIRST, READ THE @{" INSTALLATION " link instenglish 0} CHAPTER !@{UB}@{PAR}

Using RealTimeWatch is easy:@{PAR}

TEMPLATE: RealTimeWatch
 @{" QUIT/S " link optquit 0},
 @{" SECONDS/N " link optsec 0},
 @{" LOGFILE/K " link optloge 0},
 @{" DAYS/N " link optday 0}

@ENDNODE

@NODE optquit "RealTimeWatch/Optionen/ENDE/english"


QUIT: @{LINDENT 6}
Tries to quit RealTimeWatch, if specified. Of course, RealTimeWatch can
only be quit, if it runs. You will get an error message, if it's not.

No default. Also, needs no additional values.

@ENDNODE

@NODE optsec "RealTimeWatch/Optionen/SEKUNDEN/english"


SECONDS: @{LINDENT 9}
Sets the number of seconds to wait between successive hardware clock checks.
Minimum is one second, maximum is 60 seconds. Reasonable values could be
between one and five seconds.@{PAR}

The more seconds you specify, the longer it may take, until RealTimeWatch
alerts you.@{PAR}

Default is 1 (one) second. Well, I'm using 3 seconds.

@ENDNODE

@NODE optloge "RealTimeWatch/Optionen/LOGFILE/english"


LOGFILE: @{LINDENT 9}
Needs a valid path to a file, where RealTimeWatch can store the date, when
it was started. If the file does not exists, it will be created.@{PAR}

@{B}OBVIOUSLY, YOU SHOULD TAKE GREAT CARE, THAT THE FILE YOU SPECIFY IS
NOT A FILE USED BY OTHER PROGRAMS. IT WILL BE DESTROYED AFTER RealTimeWatch
HAS ACCESSED IT !@{UB}@{PAR}

No default. I am recommending something like "SYS:T/RTW_LogFile".

@ENDNODE

@NODE optday "RealTimeWatch/Optionen/DAYS/english"


DAYS: @{LINDENT 6}
Sets the number of days between successive boot-ups, the system time may vary.
Minimum is one day, maximum are 90 days. Depending on how frequently you are
using your Amiga, reasonable values are ranging from one (each day) to seven
days (shame upon you).@{PAR}

For functionality, you should specify a @{" LOGFILE " link optloge 0}, too.@{PAR}

Default is seven days (one week).

@ENDNODE

@NODE useenglish "RealTimeWatch/Bedienung/english"


The usage is kept very simple and easy. When your hardware clock is changed,
a system requester pops up, and informs you of that fact. It offers three
methods of handling the situation (the requester explains more accurate what
to do, than I do in this document):@{PAR}

1. "Older Time" or "Older Date": set the clock to what it was before it has
changed.@{PAR}

2. "Reset": set the clock to January, 1st 1978. Only there, because it's easy
to program and that you have a constant starting point, if something went
@{I}very@{UI} wrong.@{PAR}

3. "New Time" or "New Date": keeps the current date as the valid date. Useful,
if you went on holiday for three weeks, and you only allow a difference of
three days between reboots.@{PAR}

If you think, that RealTimeWatch does not work with your computer, open a shell
and type in the following:@{PAR}
@{CODE}@{LINDENT 4}
date 1-jan-78
setclock save
@{PARD}

A requester should be popping up, then...@{PAR}

You could even use "Time" preferences from Prefs, to change the date to some
days earlier or later. However, you must quit "Time" by pressing the "Save"
button. If not, the changes will only affect system time, not the hardware
clock !@{PAR}

ATTENTION: A common mistake is to switch off your computer after playing some
game. Make sure to reboot your Amiga, to verify the time has not been changed
by the game. You will think about it, if it has happened to you several times.
@{PAR}

@ENDNODE

